07420nam a22009495i 9781487583880DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191981onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875838807 a10.3138/97814875838802doi  a(DE-B1597)528032  a(OCoLC)1129181891  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aB945.P44bP695 2018 7aSCI0750002bisacsh04a144.322300aPragmatism and Purpose :bEssays Presented to Thomas A. Goudge /ced. by Leonard Sumner, John G. Slater, Fred Wilson. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©1981  a1 online resource (368 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tPart One: The Thought of C.S. Peirce -- tThe Unity of Peirce's Thought -- tPeirce on Historical Explanation -- tThe 'Proof' of Pragmatism -- tPeirce's Remarkable Theorem -- tScientific Inference: Peirce and the Humean Tradition -- tThe Labeling Problem -- tPeirce and Descartes: Doubt and the Logic of Discovery -- tJames, Santayana, Tarski, and Pragmatism -- tPeirce on Truth -- tPeirce's Conception of an Individual -- tPart Two: The Ascent of Life -- tGoudge's Contribution to Philosophy of Science -- tHistorical Narratives and Integrating Explanations -- tLife, Vis Inertiae, and the Mechanical Philosophy -- tThe Ascent of Consciousness -- tThe Interaction of Evolutionary and Genetic Theory -- tPhilosophical Aspects of the Darwinian Revolution -- tEvolution and the Necessities of Thought -- tThe Autonomy of a Logic of Discovery -- tEmergence Revisited -- tIs Biology a Different Type of Science? -- tNotes -- tList of Works Cited -- tThe Published Works of Thomas A. Goudge -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex of Names -- tIndex of Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe essays in this volume are connected with the main areas of Thomas A. Goudge's research: Peirce studies and the philosophy of science, especially the philosophy of biology. There are two sections, each opened with an essay on Goudge's contribution to the field. The first section deals with C.S. Peirce. Essays examine major features of his thought: his proof of pragmatism, his logic of relations, his semiotics, his theory of truth, his philosophy of induction, and his Scotist metaphysics of individuals. Other essays in this group relate pragmatism and pragmaticism to the work of others, in particular Collingwood, Descartes, and James and Santayana. Each involves substantial dialogue with Peirce, and a philosophical evaluation of his work and the work of others. The second is concerned with the philosophy of science. Some of the essays study the nature of scientific explanation: whether there is a logic of discovery, and whether life and teleology could be fitted into the mechanistic view of the universe that arose in the early modern period of philosophy. Various problems specifically concerning the synthetic theory of evolution are also discussed: for example, is it a theory somehow intrinsically different in kind from theories in physics? Does it yield special forms of explanation? How is it related to modern genetic theory? Other essays deal with problems arising out of an evolutionary view of life and man: for example, emergence, the place of consciousness in nature, man's knowledge of necessary truths. This is an important collection for those working in Peirce studies or the philosophy of biology, and a substantial contribution to the history of Canadian philosophy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBiologyxPhilosophy. 0aEvolution. 0aPragmatism. 7aSCIENCE / Philosophy & Social Aspects.2bisacsh1 aBurbidge, J. W., econtributor.4ctb4https://